<hl>
<seg id=1> France is considering the plan to withdraw troops from Bosnia and Herzegovina </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Paris, Sep. 1 (Xinhua News Agency) French Defense Minister Leotard said that France was considering the plan to withdraw troops from Bosnia and Herzegovina </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Leotard made the above comments in an interview with reporters from a TV station in Paris. </seg>
<seg id=4> He indicated that the US suggested to remove the arms sanction to Bosnia and Herzegovina, which would mean "possible end to international aid" and "major open conflict breaking out again", and this would lead to "heavy loss and serious consequences". </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> "In the condition that the security of the UN peace keeping force is not insured, we cannot accept to remove the arms sanction over Bosnia and Herzegovina." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> French foreign minister clearly indicated last week, "The precondition for removing the arms sanction is to withdraw all French Blue Helmet troops and all UN peace keeping forces." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Since the outburst of the Bosnia and Herzegovina conflict in Feb. 1992, France dispatched and resided 4000 troops to Bosnia and Herzegovina. </seg>
<seg id=8> France sent larger number of Blue Helmet troops to the region than other western countries. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> The US president Clinton announced on August 10 that, if the Serbs in Bosnia and Herzegovina still refuse to accept the five country peace deal, he will propose to the Security Council to pass a resolution on removing arms sanction over Bosnia and Herzegovina. If the Security Council fails to pass such resolution, he will seek to remove the arms sanction over Bosnia and Herzegovina unilaterally by the United States. </seg>
</p>
